2. The opening of this speech is an imitation of the exordium of Demosthenes' Third Olynthiac. —Longe alia, very different ; lonqe regularly goes with alius, lonye or multo with alitem—res atque pericula nostra, our danyerous position; hendiadys.

3. patriae, parentibus, arla, atque focis: these four words comprise all that is most sacred to men 3 aris et focis is a proverbial combination. — monet cavere: the use of the infinitive after moneo, like its use after hortor, is rare in Caesar and Cicero ; see on V. 9.
